Like the moon, there are places on this earth that seem distant and beyond reach. With the knowledge of what has come before, of what has been achieved by those wearing an @OMEGA speedmaster, I am pushed to explore the unknown. To seek the highest mountains, roam unfamiliar landscapes, to travel to the remote reaches of this planet. #Moonwatch #OMEGAmychoice

As the @OMEGA Speedmaster turns 60 this year, it remains one of the only watches qualified by NASA for spaceflight, and still the only one qualified for use outside the spacecraft. Tested to extreme conditions, it is designed to be worn on the surface of the moon, but fares equally well on a day to day.  #Moonwatch #OMEGAmychoice

This watch defines a time when everything became possible. The @OMEGA Speedmaster was the first watch on the moon, worn by the astronauts as part of NASA’s famed Apollo 11 mission. Holding this watch, I’m briefly transported to a time when science and human exploration was pushed to its limits.  A time defined by a single step onto the surface of something unknown, a moment when the seemingly impossible and unachievable, became reality. #Moonwatch #omegamychoice

Doa saya selalu untuk Ibu Linna adalah agar dia selalu sehat dan panjang umur, karena kami semua sangat bergantung kepadanya.

Semua urusan saya dan anak-anak menjadi tugas Ibu Linna, dan harus tuntas semuanya dengan baik sebelum dia sempat mengurusi dirinya sendiri.

Maka sebetulnya kalau orang melihat saya dan anak-anak sehat, ceria, dan berhasil dalam pekerjaan dan studi - itu karena Ibu Linna.

Itu sebabnya wanita yang baik bukan hanya menjadikan kita laki-laki yang baik, tapi juga menjadikan keluarga kita tertata dan tenteram. 
Wanita yang baik bukan hanya menjadi perhiasan terindah bagi suaminya, tapi menjadikan rumah tangganya sebagai Surga di dunia.

Dan saat badai fitnah menerjang, istri yang baik menjadi tameng, benteng, centeng, dan pengenteng beban hati.

Semoga Anda yang masih sendiri disandingkan dengan dia yang mengindahkan hati dan kehidupan Anda, dalam keluarga yang sehat, ceria, sejahtera, dan bahagia.

Dan semoga kita semua selalu berada dalam perawatan penuh cinta dari Tuhan Yang Maha Pemurah.

Semakin kita menua semakin kita akan menyadari bahwa Tuhan mengutamakan orang yang mengutamakan Tuhan.

Mohon maaf jika saya memberikan contoh seperti berikut ini:

Seorang rekan hidupnya sibuk kejar mengejar antara biaya dan pendapatan, dan mengeluh tentang kapan hidup ini memapan.

Saya anjurkan dia untuk Umrah, karena dia sudah lebih dari mampu untuk itu.

Dia menjawab singkat, bahwa dia mau upgrade mobilnya dari merk Jepang ke merk Jerman dulu.

Saya sampaikan bahwa dengan lebih mengutamakan Tuhan, kita akan lebih disejahterakan.

Tapi dia lebih ingin mobil baru daripada rindu Baitullah.

Hemm ... tapi memang setiap orang bebas memilih, hanya saja tidak ada orang yang bebas dari dampak dari pilihannya.

Marilah kita memperhatikan naik turunnya kualitas hidup ini, dan menghubungkannya dengan kualitas kedekatan kita dengan Tuhan.

Mudah-mudahan dengannya kita melihat bahwa kehidupan yang indah selalu:

Dengan nama Tuhan, karena Tuhan, dan untuk Tuhan.

Semoga doa-doa Anda segera dikabulkan oleh Tuhan Yang Maha Kaya, Maha Berkuasa, Maha Melindungi, dan Maha Pemurah.

Kami sudah bersama selama 22 tahun dan tidak sehari pun kami terpisah.

Memang tidak semua pasangan bisa selalu bersama seperti kami karena sifat dari pekerjaan dan pola hidup yang tidak memungkinkan, tapi kami membentuk dan mengatur pekerjaan dan pola hidup kami KARENA kami tidak ingin terpisah walau sehari.

Maka jadilah karir MT dan pola hidup keluarga MT.

Kami tidak mengizinkan pekerjaan dan uang menjadi lebih kuat daripada kebahagiaan kami.

Kerinduan kami untuk hidup dengan damai dan bahagia menentukan jenis pekerjaan dan pendapatan yang kami pilih, bukan sebaliknya.

Itu sebuah ketetapan yang tidak mudah, tapi kami sudah hidup damai dan bahagia bersama Audrey dan Marco dalam pilihan pola hidup ini, dan bersyukur telah diizinkan untuk bekerja dan berkarir dalam bidang yang melayani bagi kebahagiaan sesama.

Sudah tentu kebahagiaan kami menumbuhkan rasa iri dan ketidak-sukaan pada jiwa-jiwa yang tidak ikhlas diingatkan oleh Tuhan dengan kehidupan mereka yang belum damai.

Tapi, kami lebih berfokus pada kebaikan yang bisa kami bangun untuk keluarga dan yang bisa kami lebihkan untuk sesama, bukan untuk menurunkan kelas kehidupan dengan merasa geram tentang perilaku buruk orang-orang yang mendurhakai kehidupannya sendiri.

Hidup ini untuk berbahagia.

Dan bagaimana mungkin kita mencapai kebahagiaan jika sikap dan cara-cara kita tidak membahagiakan?

Semoga Tuhan mencerahkan pandangan hidup Anda, menyehatkan tubuh dan mendamaikan hati Anda, dalam keluarga yang berezeki besar dan dalam umur yang panjang.

I think it’s time for everyone to start being a little less critical of their own bodies. I have stretch marks, small breasts and cellulite. I’m not getting treatment nor am I getting anything enhanced. I don’t see any of these things as flaws.. I mean you can’t spell cellulite without 'u lit.' I’m currently working on improving my fitness, not because I want to look a certain way but because I want to feel strong. I have already received messages telling me I should get breast surgery because my breasts have gotten smaller. I’m not entirely sure why my body is their business but hey, it’s social media. I put myself out there to a large audience and I’m likely to get some negative feedback. Unfortunately they won't be able to read this because they've been blocked. I'm not putting up with negativity. Social media can be so misleading so I’m putting this message out to everyone who feels insecure. I’m not changing myself to fit a mould and neither should you. Be yourself, do it fearlessly. Remember, you have to spend the rest of your life with yourself so start loving your awkwardness, your talents, your humour, your shape, your stretch marks, your cellulite and everything that makes you unique. Self acceptance is a journey. Appreciate how far you’ve come and have faith in how far you will go ❤

During our test we'd stopped in small towns near Frankfurt for shooting. In each of them, in just a few minutes after the stop, the crowd of local residents appeared around our red Insignia Grand Sport asking a lot of questions about this eye-catching beauty from Rüsselsheim. So to us it was always quite a task to shoot the car with no people around, even at night. The interest in new Insignia is huge, especially in this area of Germany, where Opel is not just a manufacturer, with whom the destinies of many generations of people are tied, but also the part of history and culture.

Today's breakfast. French toast with avocado chocolate cream. 時々作る、熟したアボカドにココアとはちみつを混ぜたアボカドのチョコクリーム、今朝はフレンチトーストに。

Today's breakfast. 今朝はちょっと変わり種？で、色んなジャムのトースト。ひとくちひとくち食べる度に味が違う。
Today's breakfast. コーヒーが入ったフレンチトーストにマスカルポーネ、さらにチョコソースもかけて、気合いの入る月曜日の朝ごはん。今週頑張ればGWもすぐそこ！カレンダー通り5/1と2は仕事だけど、29日から気持ちはGW！
Today's breakfast. パンに塗ったのはアボカドのディップ。今日の残念なことは、オレンジの味がかなり薄かったこと。野菜や果物が常に一定の味になるわけがないことはわかっているけれど、あまりに残念な薄い味…。

Today's breakfast. 今朝は朝ごはんを作り始めようとしたところで娘が起きてきて、しかも遅寝早起きで機嫌も良くない様子だったので、急に朝ごはん作りが面倒くさくなり、自分のはこれだけ。オーブンで焼いたパンケーキにソテーしたバナナと水切りヨーグルト。娘にはオートミールのパンケーキにバナナ、温野菜サラダとコーンスープを。
予定の朝ごはんは作れなかったけど、夜勤明けで帰ってきたばかりの主人と3人で、interFMのiHeart Hawaii聞きながらのんびり食べたからオッケーオッケー。
Today's breakfast. 最近急に光の強さが変わった。明るくなり始める時間もかなり早くなったけど、冬より光がだいぶ強くなって、写真を撮るときになんか全然違う感じ。年中同じ場所で同じくらいの時間に撮っていると、そんな四季の移り変わり？みたいなのも感じて楽しいです。
Today's breakfast. 作り置きの鶏ハムとキャロットラペ、朝はパンを焼いてのせるだけ。

Today's breakfast. 娘用に焼いたバナナパンケーキ、自分のにはたっぷりとレモンカードを。
台所にコンポを置いてから前のCDを引っ張り出してきて聴くようになったんだけど、最近のちょっとしたブームは、映画アメリのサントラを聴きながら、夜中に料理すること。時間や手間がかかることはしないけど、子どもが寝てから作り置きとかお弁当用とか作るときには、最近ずっとこのCD。久しぶりに聴くとすごく良い。夜に良い。
昨夜も娘と主人が寝た後、これ聴きながらレモンカード作ってました。
Today's breakfast. 和食の作り置きがあったので、今朝はおにぎり。雑穀米にかぶの茎のふりかけを混ぜました。かぶはくり抜いて、舞茸やオートミールなどを出汁で煮て軽く味付けしたのを詰めて、さらに出汁でかぶが柔らかくなるまで煮てみたもの。なんとなく〜で作ったわりに、優しい味で娘にも好評。くり抜いたかぶは梅しそ和えに。あとはオクラのおひたしと、人参とひじきの煮物、ドライいちじく。

Day To Night, Grand Canyon National Park. 
While other images from my Day to Night series have proven to be quite challenging, this image was made even more complicated by sheer logistics. How would I create an image that showed one of the most photographed places in the world in a completely unique way? My goal was to create an image that showed the majesty and vastness of the Grand Canyon, incorporating a human scale and narrative within the scene. I photographed from the top of the Desert View Watchtower at the South Rim - in the late summer so that I could capture the summer storms - where my team and I worked for 27 hours scanning this amazing vista for all the unique moments from Day to Night. The long hours paid off and I was able to capture a single bolt of lightning just before the storm retreated into the canyon.

Day to Night, Tunnel View, Yosemite National Park. A portion of this image was featured on the cover of last year's January issue of National Geographic Magazine in honor of the 100th anniversary of the National Park Service. I am proud to celebrate our National Parks again for #nationalparksweek. 
I’ve always been inspired by the concept of using photography as a medium for capturing the passage of time. Time is something that we constantly sense, but have no concrete way of visualizing. Interestingly enough, this view, called "Tunnel View"  has remained truly timeless over the years.

In creating a Day To Night,  I photograph from locations and views that are part of our collective memory. Working from a fixed camera angle, I capture the fleeting moments of humanity and light as time passes. After photographing for up to 26 hours and over 1500 images taken, I select the best moments of the day and night. Using time as my guide, all these moments are then seamlessly blended into a single photograph, visualizing our conscious journey with time.

It is my hope that this image captures the magical experience that is Yosemite seen by millions, in the 100 operating years of the National Park Service.

Stay tuned to see more of our National Parks, including the completed images from my current series, Day to Night.

The time is meow! Our exhibition “Before Internet Cats: Feline Finds from the Archives of American Art” is now open in our Lawrence A. Fleischman Gallery, on the first floor of the @SmithsonianNPG. 
The rare documents on view in #BeforeInternetCats reflect our enduring fascination with felines. Shown here are feline finds from the @archivesamerart's collections. Creators of the cat content are (from left to right): Lenore Tawney, Mark Green, Miné Okubo, Jay DeFeo and Charles Buckley. 😸🐈🐱🐾🙀 #ArchivesCats #FelineFinds #CatsofInstagram #Catsagram #cats #purrfect

Before social media, we shared the details of our lives through snail mail. The Archives holds millions of letters that contain facts and anecdotes about the American art world, from seemingly mundane happenings to historical events. 
The papers of painter Hedda Sterne contain cat-themed correspondence from Georges Mathieu, a French painter. Here, Mathieu has embellished an oversize letter with a ribbon of adorable kittens. 
We’re the @archivesamerart taking over the @Smithsonian Instagram for the week to celebrate our new exhibition #BeforeInternetCats. 😻✉️ #ArchivesCats #FelineFinds #CatsofInstagram #Catsagram #cats #Cat-espondence

Here are some tiny snapshots of painter Jay DeFeo’s cat, Pooh. DeFeo was a Bay Area artist known for her monumental masterpiece “The Rose.” These photos—probably clipped from a contact sheet—were taken in her studio on Fillmore Street in San Francisco. 😼📸 More photos of Pooh will be on view in the #BeforeInternetCats exhibition organized by @archivesamerart, which opens Friday. 
#ArchivesCats #FelineFinds #CatsofInstagram #Catsagram #cats #artiststudio

Photographs of artists in their studios enhance our understanding of artists’ biographies, notably their working processes. For many artists, the studio is a solitary space for reflection and work. 
Cats often make ideal studio companions. They serve as sympathetic critics and elegant muses. In this photograph, Pozy the cat watches muralist Edna Reindel work in her California studio. Pozy is also the subject of the wall mural behind them. 😻🖌 Follow us at @archivesamerart for more sneak peeks at our upcoming exhibition #BeforeInternetCats.

Did you know the Smithsonian helped save the American bison from extinction? In this @smithsonianarchives photo, a group of kids look at the first bison at the National Zoo in 1899. #tbt 
When William Hornaday (later the first director of @smithsonianzoo) traveled to Montana in 1886 to collect specimens for an exhibition at the National Museum, he was surprised at how decimated the bison herds had become due to hunting. 
To educate the public about the importance of their conservation, he created an exhibition about them in the museum and even put live bison on display behind the Castle—a precursor to the Zoo in our own backyard. 
Learn about more conservation success stories this Friday through Sunday by following #EarthOptimism.

The “First Lady of Song,” Ella Fitzgerald, was born 100 years ago this month. 🎶
We’re celebrating the centennial of her birth and the legendary career that followed with this portrait on view at our @smithsoniannpg. 
It shows Fitzgerald performing, flanked by Ray Brown (left), Dizzy Gillespie (right) and Milt Jackson (far right). The photographer, William P. Gottlieb, learned to use a camera so that he could include images in his weekly music column for The Washington Post. 
Today, his photos of jazz musicians from the 1930s and ’40s are regarded as invaluable visual records of jazz’s Golden Age.

Did you know orchids make up 10 percent of the world’s plant species? But more than half of native orchids in North America are listed as threatened or endangered in some part of their home range. 
Researchers at @smithsonianenvironment are working to save the 200-plus species like this one, Galearis spectabilis, which is common in Maryland. 
They’re studying the interactions between orchids and fungi—a complex, symbiotic relationship in which each of the orchids’ life stages depend to some extent on specific fungi. 
Learn about our conservation efforts and successes this week as we share stories on Facebook and Twitter with #EarthOptimism.

Happy #Easter! This early 20th-century postcard is one of more than 3,000 real photo postcards in our @amhistorymuseum​'s Photographic History Collection.

Real photo postcards, made on thick photo paper with the postcard info pre-printed on the back, were popular from around 1900 to World War I.

In 1907, postal regulations changed to allow senders to put messages AND addresses on the back—before, only addresses went there. This kept the front free from writing and the image unmarked.

@smithsoniangardens redesigns this area in symmetrical patterns every few seasons, and we’re digging these new 🌷🌷🌷. This space behind our Castle building is called The Parterre (from the French for “on the ground”), which is a style typically associated with the Victorian era.

“That belongs in a museum!” While the Ruby Slippers step out, you'll still be able to see iconic American entertainment objects at our @amhistorymuseum: props from "Indiana Jones." A hat and whip Harrison Ford used in the film series will go on display where the Ruby Slippers are now. (The shoes will undergo some much-needed conservation—the last day to see them for a while is April 23.) We promise to keep the snakes far away.

The Ruby Slippers are off to see the Wizard in the conservation lab.👠 April 23 is the last day to see them for a while at @amhistorymuseum. 
Dorothy (played by Judy Garland) wore them in the 1939 film “The Wizard of Oz,” and they’ve been on display almost continuously since their donation to the museum in 1979. Now they’re showing their age. 
Last fall, nearly 6,500 fans donated to our Kickstarter campaign, #KeepThemRuby. With that help, the Ruby Slippers will be getting some much-needed conservation and will be placed in a new state-of-the-art case to keep them sparkling for generations to come.

Once thought to be extinct, black-footed ferrets are rebounding through Smithsonian science. 
The recovery of the species started with just 18 animals, whose offspring came to the Smithsonian Conservation Biology Institute in 1988. Since then, 726 black-footed ferrets have been born there, and several hundred of those have been reintroduced to the wild. 
It’s one of many conservation success stories that will be shared at our #EarthOptimism Summit, held over Earth Day weekend. We’re convening scientists, thought leaders, philanthropists, conservationists and civic leaders to highlight what’s working in conservation. Wild Garlic & Watercress Pesto by @happyskinkitchen 💚

Ingredients:
A bunch of wild garlic (leaves & flowers)
¾ cup of cashew (you can use pine nuts as well)
A generous handful of fresh basil leaves
1 cup of chopped watercress
2 tablespoons of olive oil
The juice of 1 lemon (use half if you don’t like too lemony)
1 tablespoon of Love Raw Simple Greens
2 tablespoons of nutritional yeast
Salt & pepper to taste
Pasta of your choice (I have used brown rice spaghetti)
To sprinkle on top: fresh chives
.
Place the cashew in the food processor and blitz until you have a coarse mixture. Add all the other ingredients and blitz again for at least 1 minute until you have a creamy consistency. If you find the pesto too thick add a splash of water or more olive oil. 
Cook the pasta of your choice according to the cooking instructions. Mix about 2 tablespoon of pesto in each plate and sprinkle with the fresh chopped chives.  #vegancommunity #vegan #govegan #veganism #vegano

Ay Manizales del alma! Mi corazón con ustedes. 
Los científicos llevan mucho tiempo advirtiendo de que el aumento global de temperaturas provoca cambios en el régimen de precipitaciones. La base del argumento es fácil de entender: más calor equivale a más energía en las atmósfera, por consiguiente, más vapor de agua y más actividad en el sistema. Es difícil predecir cómo cambiarán las lluvias exactamente en cada lugar del mundo, pero sí saben que, debido a la mayor cantidad de energía presente en la atmósfera, se harán más habituales los fenómenos extremos, como lo que sucedió en la madrugada de nuestro #ManizalesDelAlma que llovió fuertemente y sin parar durante dos horas superando los 143 milímetros; la misma cantidad que se puede acumular en un mes dejando muertos, heridos y desaparecidos. 
De seguir aumentando los gases efecto invernadero y la temperatura en nuestro planeta seguirán aumentando considerablemente las precipitaciones fuertes y el riesgo de avalanchas e inundaciones.

Terletak di pulau Honshu, Jepang, mempunyai tinggi  3776 meter dpl, Gunung Fuji (atau kadang disebut Fuji-san) adalah puncak tertinggi di dataran Jepang. Ketika musim dingin puncak gunung ini bersalju yang membuatnya semakin terlihat kokoh tapi tetap indah dipandang, gunung ini adalah simbol dari kota Tokyo. Gunung Fuji ini juga memiliki karakteristik sebagai gunung berapi. Meskipun letusan terakhirnya tercatat terakhir di tahun 1707, gunung ini masih dianggap sebagai gunung berapi aktif dan berisiko. Dulu bagi wanita dilarang untuk mendaki Gunung Fuji hingga akhirnya peraturan itu dicabut di tahun 1912, hingga kini tercatat semakin banyak orang yang ingin mendaki gunung Fuji.

✨
Moreover acclaimed director Hayao Miyazaki, of Ghibli's Spirited Away fame, is widely believed to have taken inspiration from @hotelgajoentokyo's marvelous architecture to make the castle featured in the Oscar-winning movie. 🎏🏯

There are six great aquifers in the world. In North America our great aquifer is the Ogallala—it stretches from South Dakota to the Texas panhandle. Twenty percent of our food and 40 percent of our beef rely on the aquifer. It’s unfortunate that we’ve pumped the equivalent of two Lake Eries out, setting the stage for a new desert in the Texas panhandle and southern Kansas in the immediate future.

The aquifer recharges at different rates. Nebraska wins the water lottery; it is the only place you can see Ogallala water at the surface. The Ogallala takes a long time to recharge in Texas, where there are the most wells, the least regulation, the hottest temperatures (even before climate change), and the slowest recharge. Entire communities in this area are already running out of water.

Scarcity of water, fragile infrastructure, small dust bowls, the family farm crisis, Big Ag, and global urbanization leave some behind with few options. Small towns are disintegrating around their residents. There is rampant meth and opioid addiction in some of these places. If your hot water heater breaks, there isn’t anyone in your entire county that can fix it.

I am from the Midwest, and the pain rural folks have gone through showed up this election. I saw this frustration first-hand working on the Ogallala aquifer story that ran in the August 2016 issue of National Geographic, but I never thought the level of frustration of these communities would manifest itself in this way. @natgeo @natgeocreative @thephotosociety

Wood River Nebraska - This was the last night of the last trip for an @natgeo assignment on the Ogallala Aquifer. I had bedded down in the blind when the cranes started to land for the night just outside… then the storm rolled in. Sand Hill Cranes are the grassland birds of the great plains. They migrate from Siberia to northern Mexico. They counted 413,000 Sandhill Cranes on this evening… more than they’ve ever counted before. These conservation groups are working like crazy to keep 20 miles of the Platte River braided and perfect habitat for the cranes that come through their area. @thephotosociety @natgeo @natgeocreative

A very large and curious Maori wrasse followed our team around Sno Reef on the Great Barrier Reef. This big guy weighed several hundred pounds and had spear wounds from unsuccessful poaching encounters. The corals on the Great Barrier Reef are now in the midst of another unprecedented coral bleaching event. High sea temperatures in 2016 caused 90% of the 1200 mile long reef to bleach, a process where the tiny coral polyp loses its symbiotic algae due to heat stress. The algae provide valuable life sustaining nutrients to the coral and give it its color. If conditions improve quickly  enough some corals can recover from a bleach event while others die and become covered in algae. Scientist estimate that 20% + of the Great Barrier Reef corals did not recover during the 2016 event. The extent of the 2017 bleach is yet to be known. Sequential bleaching events weakens the corals resilience and speeds the death of the reef.
